e: large;"><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">The Spanish were quartered near town of Turnhout by Breda and Prince Maurice made a surprise attack on them. &nbsp;The Spanish sought to escape from this onslaught and retreated - however, Maurice had forseen this action and had already dispatched Sir Francis Vere (head of his English allied troops) and Count Hohenlo to intercept this movement. Vere attacked in his customary vigour and put the Spanish force into considerable confusion. &nbsp;This gave Maurice''s main force time to catch up from behind and totally route the whole Spanish army. &nbsp;Some two thousand Spanish troops were killed and about five hundred taken prisoner. The battle is particularly noteworthy as it was the first time that the cavalry was armed with carbines which proved stunningly successful - the allied victory was gained with the loss of only some ten men !</span></span></span></p><p><span style="font-size: large;"><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">After Turnhout Maurice gathered his men and in three months secured the whole of the country north of the Rhine with all its towns and fortresses, clearing them of all Spanish presence. &nbsp;Throughout the whole campain he was aided by English troops sent by Elizabeth to support the Protestant cause in the United Provinces.</span></span></span></p><!-- End Description AucLister --></font><br> 
 
