ered near town of Turnhout by Breda and Prince Maurice made a surprise attack on them. &nbsp;The Spanish sought to escape from this onslaught and retreated - however, Maurice had forseen this action and had already dispatched Sir Francis Vere (head of his English allied troops) and Count Hohenlo to intercept this movement. Vere attacked in his customary vigour and put the Spanish force into considerable confusion. &nbsp;This gave Maurice''s main force time to catch up from behind and totally route the whole Spanish army. &nbsp;Some two thousand Spanish troops were killed and about five hundred taken prisoner. The battle is particularly noteworthy as it was the first time that the cavalry was armed with carbines which proved stunningly successful - the allied victory was gained with the loss of only some ten men ! &nbsp;The cavalry firing carbines can be seen very clearly on the jeton.</span></span></span></p><!-- End Description AucLister --></font><br> 
 
